ce:section.ce:para:
Based on the different interactions and enhancement effects of NPs on CL reactions, a sensor array was fabricated by employing three kinds of oxidants including H2O2, AgNO3, and K3Fe(CN)6 as sensing elements. CL responses of the luminol-different oxidants to five NPs, including Cit-AgNPs, Cyst-AgNPs, Cit-AuNPs, CTAB–AuNPs and CTAB-AuNRs that were selected as target analytes in this study, were thoroughly assessed. The results indicated that CL was enhanced in different degrees with the introduction of these NPs (Fig. 4), due to their catalytic effect. Therefore identification of various NPs is possible by using discriminative CL signal changes of this array system. It's worthy to mention that this sensor array is simple, facile and cost-effective in instrumentation. The responses were accounted based on the difference of CL intensities, ΔI=I − I0, that I and I0 were the CL intensities of luminol-oxidant In presence and absence of NPs. The discrimination ability of proposed sensor array for five NPs in five concentration levels including C, C/2, C/4, C/5, C/10 (C = synthesis concentration) was tested. To provide clear evidence, the ΔI matrices were subjected to linear discriminant analysis (LDA) as a statistical analysis process for differentiating between various objects. Three replicates were done for every NPs and we successfully discriminated NPs by using the training matrix generated from ΔI patterns. NPs were classified into five discrete classes by using the LDA analysis (Fig. 5
                        ). In the proposed method, NPs induced distinct array response and clustered into separated groups, showing that chemiluminescence sensor array is able to provide a sensitive way to discriminate various NPs. Additionally, The response patterns were statistically analyzed using hierarchical cluster analysis (HCA) that is a statistical classification system. Similarly to the LDA, NPs are classified into different clustering groups and successful clear discrimination of these analytes was achieved (Fig. 6
                        ).The heat map was used for visualization of the particular patterns of responses (ΔI) of each NPs which were obtained from the three sensor elements (Fig. 7
                        ). A heat map (or heatmap) is a two-dimensional graphical representation of numerical results where colors represent corresponding numbers. This visual tool can be very practical since it can provide a quick and simple visitable concept of data quantities that is easier to compare. In the map Guide, dark red and dark blue show the maximum and the minimum numbers respectively. By the increasing the values, the color goes from coldest color (dark blue) to warmest color (dark red). It could be understood from the heatmaps that various NPs presented distinguished enhancing CL responses patterns. For further investigation, the responses of NPs at the same concentration (0.5 nM) on the sensor array were measured and satisfactory discrimination was obtained (Fig. 8
                        ).
